	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Wed Oct 24, 2012 9:49 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Game design Sins</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I'm starting to collect a <a href="http://pineight.com/mw/index.php?title=Action_53#Subjective_requirements" class="postlink">list of sins</a> as part of my multicart project. Far too many of the games in Action 52 have at least one of these sins:<br /><ul><li><a href="http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/HitboxDissonance" class="postlink">Inconsistent collision detection</a> </li><li><a href="http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DamnYouMuscleMemory" class="postlink">Nonstandard control mapping</a>, such as B to jump and A to attack </li><li>Premature application of <a href="http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/NotTheFallThatKillsYou" class="postlink">falling damage</a> </li><li><a href="http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/UnwinnableByDesign" class="postlink">Deliberate unwinnable situations</a>, especially those caused by the combination of SMB1-style <a href="http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RatchetScrolling" class="postlink">ratchet scrolling</a> with poor level design </li><li><a href="http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/UnwinnableByMistake" class="postlink">Important events failing to trigger</a> </li></ul><br />Other sins include making important things hard to see through poor contrast or through overly busy backgrounds (Battletoads GB), the camera not showing enough in front of the player character (Lode Runner) or what's on the other side of a jump that the player is expected to make (Balloon Kid), too-small collision areas for grabbing ladders (RoboCop, Home Alone NES), level design not giving the player the chance to play with elements such as moving platforms before they are critical, and unskippable cut scenes between a respawn point and a boss fight. I don't agree with all of the <a href="http://devmag.org.za/2012/07/19/13-more-tips-for-making-a-fun-platformer/" class="postlink">&quot;13 More Tips for Making a Fun Platformer&quot; by Diorgo Jonkers</a>, but they're still worth a read.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


